04807nam a22006375i 9780231541442DE-B159720210824034702.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210824t20162016nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a2015039970  a(OCoLC)984622618  a97802315414427 a10.7312/honn177162doi  a(DE-B1597)468984  a(OCoLC)949931582  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY00aB809.3b.H667 2016 7aPHI0400002bisacsh  aCK 17202rvk0(DE-625)rvk/159515:117971 aHonneth, Axel, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aRecognition or Disagreement :bA Critical Encounter on the Politics of Freedom, Equality, and Identity /cAxel Honneth, Jacques Rancière; ed. by Katia Genel, Jean-Philippe Deranty. 1aNew York, NY : bColumbia University Press, c[2016] 4c©2016  a1 online resource (240 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aNew Directions in Critical Theory ;v3000tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPart I. Setting the Stage -- tOne. Jacques Rancière and Axel Honneth -- tTwo. Between Honneth and Rancière -- tPart II. A Critical Encounter -- tThree. Critical Questions on the Theory of Recognition -- tFour. Remarks on the Philosophical Approach of Jacques Rancière -- tFive. A Critical Discussion -- tPart III. The Method of Critical Theory: Propositions -- tSix. The Method of Equality: Politics and Poetics -- tSeven. Of the Poverty of Our Liberty: The Greatness and Limits of Hegel’s Doctrine of Ethical Life -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex -- tBackmatter0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAxel Honneth is best known for his critique of modern society centered on a concept of recognition. Jacques Rancière has advanced an influential theory of modern politics based on disagreement. Underpinning their thought is a concern for the logics of exclusion and domination that structure contemporary societies. In a rare dialogue, these two philosophers explore the affinities and tensions between their perspectives to provoke new ideas for social and political change.Honneth sees modern society as a field in which the logic of recognition provides individuals with increasing possibilities for freedom and is a constant catalyst for transformation. Rancière sees the social as a policing order and the political as a force that must radically assert equality. Honneth claims Rancière's conception of the political lies outside of actual historical societies and involves a problematic desire for egalitarianism. Rancière argues that Honneth's theory of recognition relies on an overly substantial conception of identity and subjectivity. While impassioned, their exchange seeks to advance critical theory's political project by reconciling the rift between German and French post-Marxist traditions and proposing new frameworks for justice.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aCritical theory. 0aPolitical sciencexPhilosophy. 0aRecognition (Philosophy) 7aPHILOSOPHY / Movements / Critical Theory.2bisacsh1 aDeranty, Jean-Philippe, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDeranty, Jean-Philippe, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aGenel, Katia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGenel, Katia, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aHonneth, Axel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRancière, Jacques, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aRancière, Jacques, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertColumbia University Press Complete eBook-Package 2016z978311063857840uhttps://doi.org/10.7312/honn1771640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/978023154144